# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: appkit-macos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] AppKit comprises a collection of Objective-C classes and protocols that can be used to build an application in OpenStep/Cocoa.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] These classes can also be used in Swift through its Objective-C bridge.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] Xcode has built-in functionality for developing a Cocoa application using AppKit, including the ability to visually design user interfaces with Interface Builder.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] It relies heavily on patterns like reference types, delegation, notifications, target–action, and model–view–controller.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] A sign of the NeXTSTEP heritage, AppKit's classes and protocols still use the "NS" prefix.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] Most of the applications bundled with macOS—for example, the Finder, TextEdit, Calendar, and Preview—use AppKit to provide their user interface.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] macOS, iOS, iPadOS, and tvOS also support other UI frameworks, including UIKit, which is derived from AppKit and uses many similar structures, and SwiftUI, a Swift-only declarative UI framework.
[src:appkit-macos/appkit] Prior to macOS Catalina, macOS also supported Carbon, a UI framework derived from the Macintosh Toolbox.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Aqua was introduced at the 2000 Macworld conference in San Francisco.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] It was first released in July with iMovie 2, and with Mac OS X 10.0 the following year.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Aqua is the successor to Platinum, which was used in Mac OS 8, Mac OS 9, and developer releases of Rhapsody (including Mac OS X Server 1.0).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Apple continually revised Aqua with subsequent operating system revisions, including adding SwiftUI design standards and Swift language support into Aqua’s interface, and implementing its design into newer products such as the iPhone.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In 2013, Apple heavily revised the skeuomorphic user interface to adopt a flat design.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In 2025, Apple introduced the Liquid Glass design language across their operating systems.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] For years, Apple had been trying and failing to produce a next-generation Mac OS operating system, including projects code-named Pink, Taligent, and Copland.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X was ultimately built on NeXTSTEP, after Apple purchased NeXT and its CEO, Steve Jobs, returned to Apple, the company he had cofounded.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Early versions of Mac OS X, called Rhapsody, was a developer release that had an interim user interface, blending MacOS 8's "Platinum" and OpenStep looks.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Rhapsody approach was ultimately abandoned, and the new operating system was dubbed Mac OS X in 1998.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Early developer previews of Mac OS X shipped with an interface similar to Rhapsody, combining classic Mac OS and NextStep.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The final operating system interface, Aqua, would be unveiled at Macworld Expo in January 2000.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Aqua uses blue, white, and gray as the principal colors throughout its style.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Window toolbars, window backgrounds, buttons, menus and other interface elements are all found in either of these colors.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] For instance, toolbars and sidebars are often grey or metal-colored, window backgrounds and popup menus are white and buttons (in older systems also scrollbar handles) are accented with a bright blue.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In versions of OS X prior to OS X Yosemite, most controls have a "glass" or "gel" effect applied to them.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] David Pogue described this effect as "lickable globs of Crest Berrylicious Toothpaste Gel".
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] macOS has few native customization options to change the overall look of the system.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Users can choose a graphite appearance instead of the default blue one.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] When using the graphite appearance, controls have a slate-like, grey-blue or grey color, including the primary window controls which are red, yellow and green with the default appearance.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The appearance option was added at the behest of developers and users who found the blue appearance garish or unprofessional.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] OS X Yosemite added a dark mode that darkens the predominantly white menubar and Dock.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Users can also freely choose a highlight color for text and file selection.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Historically, Aqua had two window designs: the default Aqua windows and "brushed metal" windows.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Aqua windows typically have a metal-like or gray titlebar with three buttons on the left side (for closing, minimizing and zooming or entering fullscreen mode).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Visually, these buttons used to be placed on top, but later appeared 'sunken' into the window.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Aqua windows have almost no frame or outside border, instead drop shadows are used to separate and distinguish active from inactive windows.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The aesthetic of the window backgrounds changed from pin-striped to white backgrounds.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Brushed-metal windows had a thick frame with a metallic texture or dark-gray background and sunken buttons and inner frames.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] They had the additional property of being draggable at every point of the frame instead of just the titlebar and toolbar.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Brushed-metal windows have been largely phased out since Leopard and become visually indistinctive from Aqua windows.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In addition to titlebars, windows can also have toolbars with separate buttons.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Up to Leopard, toolbars were visually separated from the titlebar and had the same background as the window frame or were pin-striped.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Leopard introduced a unified style that extended the metal-like background of the titlebar to the toolbar, making it appear as one whole.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Optionally, a separator could be placed between the titlebar and the toolbar to mimic the previous style.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] OS X Yosemite brought a more-compact version of the toolbar that fused the titlebar and toolbar together, made it shorter and removed the window title (for example, in Safari 8 and later).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Drawers are accessory sidebar views that can slide out from any edge of a window except the top edge.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] They can be resized perpendicular to their window edge but follow the window's size in the other direction.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Drawers were once frequently used to display controls and information that did not need to be always visible, but Apple now recommends against their use.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Sheets are dialog boxes that are modal to a specific window.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] When opened, they are thrust towards the user like a sheet of paper, hence the name.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] They are partially transparent and focus attention on the content of the sheet.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The parent window's controls are disabled until the sheet is dismissed, but the user is able to continue work in other windows (including those in the same application) while the sheet is open.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Menus are backed with a slightly translucent solid gray, and when menu items are highlighted they appear blue.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In application menus, which run in a single bar across the top of the screen, keyboard shortcuts appear to the right-hand side of the menu whilst the actual menu item is on the left.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In Yosemite, the menus are much more translucent and have a blur effect.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Drop down menus for use in windows themselves are also available in several varieties.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The standard "pop up" menu is white with a blue end cap with opposing arrows, whilst 'pull down' menus only have one downward facing arrow in the end cap.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] 'Pull down' menus are available in four different Aqua varieties, most of which have fallen into disuse in later macOS releases.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Text boxes are black on white text with a sunken effect border.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In addition to regular square text boxes, rounded search text boxes are available .
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] For more extensive text requirements, there is also a multi-line text field.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] A combined text box and pull down menu is available, which allows the user to type in a value in addition to choosing from a menu.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] There is also a combination textbox and picker control, which allows the user to type in a date and time or edit it with directional buttons.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X 10.4 introduced a new interface element that allows the user to drag non-editable 'tokens' to a text box, between which text can be typed.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Whitespace before and after the tokens is trimmed.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Standard push buttons with rounded corners are available in two varieties: white and blue.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] A blue button is the default action, and in OS releases prior to Yosemite, would appear to pulse to prompt the user to carry out that action.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The action of a blue button can usually also be invoked with the return key.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] White buttons are usually associated with all other actions.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Also available are rounded bevel buttons, designed to hold an icon; standard square buttons; glass square buttons and round buttons.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In addition, circular, purple online help buttons are available which display help relative to the current task when clicked.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Disclosure triangles, although technically buttons, allow views of controls to be shown and hidden to preserve space.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In macOS, empty check boxes are small, white rounded rectangles.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] When they are checked, they turn blue and a checkmark is present.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] They are essentially buttons which can be toggled on or off.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Radio buttons are similar in appearance and behaviour except that they are circular and contain a dot instead of a check.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Radio buttons are classed into groups of which only one can be activated at a time.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In Yosemite, a short animation was added to show the checkbox or radio button filling in.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] All table views can use alternating blue and white row backgrounds.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Two main types of loading/saving progress indicator are available: a progress bar or a monochromatic spinning wheel (not the spinning pinwheel).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The progress bar itself is available in two varieties: indeterminate, which simply shows diagonal blue and white stripes in animation with no measure of progress; or determinate, which shows a blue pulsing bar against a white background proportional to the percentage of a task completed.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The spinning wheel indicator, also found in the Mac OS X startup screen since version 10.2, is simply a series of 12 increasingly darker grey lines arranged circularly, like the side view of a spoked wheel rotating clockwise.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Many other interfaces have adopted this device, including the Firefox and Camino web browsers and many Web 2.0-influenced web sites.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In Yosemite, the progress bar was changed to a thin, light gray.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The "indeterminate" variation kept the pulses, but slower and spaced out.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] A progress indicator now appears during boot, replacing the spinning wheel indicator found in earlier versions.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Sliders are available in three types: one with tick marks and a triangular scrubber, one with a round scrubber and no tick marks and a circular slider which can be rotated.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] All are available horizontally or vertically.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The circular slider is simply a gray dot on a white circle which can be rotated to set values.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] macOS has a standard control for picking colors which appears as a regular square button with a color sample in the middle.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] When clicked, it shows the standard macOS color palette.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Tabs in macOS are nearly identical to push buttons, with the unselected tab(s) being white and the selected tab being blue.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Image "wells" are also available: a small, sunken container into which image files can be dropped.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] When the well contains an image, it can display a thumbnail representation of the file's contents.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Apple used Lucida Grande as the system typeface from the first release Cheetah to Mavericks.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Occasionally, Apple also used Helvetica and Helvetica Neue, such as in applications like Mail and iPhoto.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Many of these effects can be turned off by the user or are only available on supported hardware.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Aqua is powered by the display server Quartz Compositor.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Panther version of the Aqua interface shows several changes, most notably brushed metal.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Jobs introduced the Aqua interface as an attempt by Apple to create a more powerful interface for professional users, while making an approachable product for new computer users.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X 10.2 "Jaguar" brought flatter interface elements, such as new buttons and drop-down menus, and reduced the transparency to tone down the pinstripes in windows and menus.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] These trends continued in subsequent Mac OS X releases.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In Mac OS X Panther buttons were made to appear sunken into their surroundings, following a general trend of more flattened interface elements in the operating system.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The traditional pinstripes were replaced with a much subtler theme, most notably in the menu bar, and the use of transparency was again reduced (for example in the title bars of inactive windows).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Tabs also changed; they were made flatter and the whole tab area was sunken rather than raised.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Tab buttons were centered on the top border of the tab area.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] New icons appeared across the system, including a new flatter, glossier Finder icon and a new System Preferences icon.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Panther also featured an increased use of the "Brushed Metal" look, especially to the Finder and Safari web browser.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Brushed Metal had first appeared in QuickTime Player 4.0 in 1999.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Apple's Human Interface Guidelines stated that the brushed metal interface be used for programs that mimic the operation or interface of common real world devices (skeuomorphism).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Tiger brought more subtle changes, including the unified titlebar scheme.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Pinstripes were removed from the menu bar entirely and replaced with a glossy, white look.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Tabs were altered to appear as normal segmented buttons.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Apple menu icon was toned down to a more matte appearance and the new Spotlight search utility was permanently bound to the very right of the menu bar in the same color and gradient of the Apple menu.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Leopard brought wide-ranging changes to Aqua.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Dock's design, when placed on the left or right side, changed to a black translucent background with a white border and rounded corners.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Context menus had slightly-rounded corners and numerous icons were redesigned, including folder icons and System Preferences icons.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Snow Leopard made almost no changes to Aqua.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Most notably, the context menu of Dock items changed from a solid white to a translucent black.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Mac OS X Lion introduced many changes inspired by iOS that persisted in OS X Mavericks as well as OS X Yosemite, although the latter changed the overall aesthetic.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Scrollbars were removed and scrollbar handles turned into thin, semi-transparent bars that disappear when not used.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The corner radii of push buttons were reduced, giving an appearance similar to Mac OS 8 and 9.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The gel-like appearance of most components was replaced with a slightly glossy and flatter look.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Window backgrounds became slightly brighter and window corners were rounded.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] OS X Mountain Lion brought only minor changes and changed the Dock's appearance into a frosted-glass style, with rounded corners, rectangular indicator lights, a new diagonal separator and a new Trash icon.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] OS X Mavericks dispensed with several rich and ornamental designs, reflecting the design overhaul in iOS 7.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The applications Calendar, Contacts, and Notes respectively lost their leather, book, and notepad skeuomorphic appearance (all introduced in Lion).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Linen textures in Notification Center and Launchpad were removed as well and replaced with simple gray backgrounds.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Dock was made to appear white when set to pop up sideways, somewhat akin to its original design when at such, albeit with the overall design retained from previous skeuomorphic versions.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In OS X Yosemite, many of the Aqua elements and icons were simplified and flattened, following a similar design change in iOS 7.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Apple incorporated the same saturated frosted-glass effect, called "Vibrancy", across the system.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Examples include the Dock, the menubar, sidebars, Notification Center and Mission Control.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] A similar effect was applied to toolbars, but they maintained their gray appearance.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Toolbar buttons became white and Apple introduced a more compact type of toolbar that removed the window title, but retained the toolbar buttons (for example, in Safari).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Certain controls, such as checkboxes and radio buttons, gained animations, whereas animations in other places were removed, such as the "poof" animation when removing an icon from the Dock and the "cube" animation when fast-switching to another user account.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Apple changed the system typeface to Helvetica Neue.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Yosemite also added a "dark theme" that can be enabled by the user in the settings which makes the dock and menu bar black.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] OS X El Capitan made only minor changes to Aqua.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The white toolbar buttons regained a slightly glossy look, the spinning pinwheel was redesigned and the Vibrancy effect was reduced in certain areas, such as Mission Control.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The system typeface was changed once more, to Apple's own San Francisco typeface, concurrent with iOS 9 and following the typeface's release in watchOS in April 2015.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] These changes continued throughout macOS Sierra, High Sierra, Mojave, and Catalina.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] macOS Big Sur brought major changes to Aqua design that brings it in line with other Apple platforms such as iOS and iPadOS.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Dock was detached from the screen edge and more rounded on all corners.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The icons were all squircle-shaped and took on more noticeable depth in general.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Titlebars lost their gradient chrome, opting for a flat white look, and the titlebar text was now bold, and inline with toolbar items, which are no longer contained within a distinct background.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Modal dialogs had changed significantly, only being as large as the content inside; laid out with a large icon at the top, text in the center, and buttons at the bottom.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Sheets no longer slided out like paper from under the titlebar, instead more simply fading in from the center of the window.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Unified sidebars have become more commonplace and are the default for all applications.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Windows now had more rounded corners and take on a tint from the user's wallpaper, akin to Windows 11's Mica effect.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The menubar was now completely transparent, using a strong blur to differentiate from the background.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] This revision of Aqua continued to be used in macOS Monterey, Ventura, Sonoma, and Sequoia.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] As part of a larger movement to standardise the visual design language across their products, macOS adopted Liquid Glass with macOS Tahoe.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Windows version of Safari, in version 3, included a functional Aqua look and feel that was very similar to macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] As of version 4, a more Windows-like theme was employed using the standard Windows user interface controls and window border.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] QuickTime for Windows uses the same theme as seen in older versions of QuickTime for macOS, with brushed-metal windows and Aqua buttons on top.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Much of Aqua's original design resembled the translucent two-tone look of Apple's contemporary hardware.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In 2003 and 2004, Apple moved to the use of brushed aluminium in their industrial design (such as with the aluminium Apple Cinema Displays).
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] This somewhat inconsistent mix of interface styles has been controversial among the Mac community.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] In the past, Apple has threatened legal action against those who make themes similar to their look and feel.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] The Mac skinning community took exception to Apple's heavy-handed actions against all Aqua lookalikes.
[src:appkit-macos/aqua-user-interface] Stardock's Brad Wardell contrasted the company's litigious approach with Microsoft's approach to incorporating third-party skins into Windows XP.
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] Core Animation can animate any visual element, and it provides a unified way of accessing Core Image, Core Video, and the other Quartz technologies.
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] Core Animation rendering can be accelerated by a graphics processor (GPU).
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] Animated sequences execute in a thread independent from the main run loop, allowing application processing to occur while the animation is in progress.
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] In this way, application performance is not affected, and animations can be stopped, reversed, or *retargeted* while in progress.
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] Core Animation first appeared in Mac OS X Leopard, but actually first emerged from the iPhone software team.
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] It was shown publicly for the first time on August 7, 2006 during WWDC 2006.
[src:appkit-macos/core-animation] At the Macworld Expo 2007, Apple announced that the iPhone runs a specially adapted version of OS X and uses Core Animation.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:appkit-macos/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Mac OS X succeeded the classic Mac OS, the primary Macintosh operating system from 1984 to 2001.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Its underlying architecture came from NeXT's NeXTSTEP, as a result of Apple's acquisition of NeXT, which also brought Steve Jobs back to Apple.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The first desktop version, Mac OS X 10.0, was released on March 24, 2001.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apart from OS X Lion, all versions from Mac OS X Leopard onwards are UNIX 03 certified.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Each of Apple's other contemporary operating systems, including iOS, iPadOS, watchOS, tvOS, audioOS and visionOS, are derivatives of macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] During its history, macOS has supported three major processor architectures: the initial version supported PowerPC-based Macs only, with support for Intel-based Macs beginning with OS X Tiger 10.4.4 and support for ARM-based Apple silicon Macs beginning with macOS Big Sur.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Support for PowerPC-based Macs was dropped with OS X Snow Leopard, and it was announced at the 2025 Worldwide Developers Conference that macOS Tahoe will be the last to support Intel-based Macs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Unlike versions of the classic Mac OS, Mac OS X retained the same major version number (10) for almost two decades, with major releases only incrementing the *minor* version number (e.g.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Since 2020, Apple increments the major version component in each major release, with macOS Big Sur getting version number 11.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2025, the numbering scheme was changed once again, now using the number of the year that follows the release year (e.g. macOS Tahoe, released in September 2025, has a version number 26).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] A prominent part of macOS's original brand identity was the use of the Roman numeral X, pronounced "ten", as well as code naming each release after species of big cats, and later, places within California.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple shortened the name to "OS X" in 2011 and then changed it to "macOS" in 2016 to align with the branding of Apple's other operating systems.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2020, macOS Big Sur was presented as version 11—a marked departure after 16 releases of macOS 10—but the naming convention continued to reference places within California.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2025, Apple unified the version number across all of its products to align with the year after their WWDC announcement, so the release announced at the 2025 WWDC, macOS Tahoe, is macOS 26.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The heritage of what would become macOS originated at NeXT, a company founded by Steve Jobs following his departure from Apple in 1985.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] There, the Unix-like NeXTSTEP operating system was developed, before being launched in 1989.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The kernel of NeXTSTEP is based upon the Mach kernel, which was originally developed at Carnegie Mellon University, with additional kernel layers and low-level user space code derived from parts of FreeBSD and other BSD operating systems.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Its graphical user interface was built on top of an object-oriented GUI toolkit using the Objective-C programming language.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Throughout the 1990s, Apple had tried to create a "next-generation" OS to succeed its classic Mac OS through the Taligent, Copland and Gershwin projects; however, all were eventually abandoned.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This led Apple to acquire NeXT in 1997, allowing NeXTSTEP, later called OPENSTEP, to serve as the basis for Apple's next-generation operating system.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The acquisition also led to Steve Jobs returning to Apple as interim and later permanent CEO, shepherding the transformation of the programmer-friendly OPENSTEP into a system that would be adopted by Apple's primary market of home users and creative professionals.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The project was codenamed "Rhapsody" before being officially named Mac OS X.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The "X" in Mac OS X's name represents the Roman numeral for the number ten, and Apple has stated that it should be pronounced "ten" in this context; it is also commonly pronounced like the letter "X".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The iPhone X, iPhone XR and iPhone XS all later followed this convention.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The first version of Mac OS X, Mac OS X Server 1.0, was a transitional product, featuring an interface resembling the classic Mac OS, though it was not compatible with software designed for the older system; consumer releases of Mac OS X included more backward compatibility.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Mac OS applications could be rewritten to run natively via the Carbon API, with many alternatively able to be run directly through the Classic Environment albeit with a reduction in performance.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The consumer version of Mac OS X was launched in March 2001 with Mac OS X 10.0.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Reviews were variable, with many praising its sophisticated, glossy Aqua interface, but criticizing it for sluggish performance.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] With Apple's popularity at a low, the developer of FrameMaker, Adobe Inc., declined to develop new versions of it for Mac OS X.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] *Ars Technica* columnist John Siracusa, who reviewed every major OS X release up to 10.10, described the early releases in retrospect as "dog-slow, feature poor" and Aqua as "unbearably slow and a huge resource hog".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple rapidly developed several new releases of Mac OS X.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple released Mac OS X 10.1 in October 2001, delivering quality of life enhancements.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Beginning in January 2002, Apple preinstalled Mac OS X as the default operating system on all Macs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Later that year Apple released Mac OS X Jaguar (version 10.2), the first version to publicly use its code name in marketing and advertisements.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] As the operating system evolved, it moved away from the classic Mac OS, with applications being added and removed.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Considering music to be a key market, Apple developed the iPod music player and music software for the Mac, including iTunes and GarageBand.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Targeting the consumer and media markets, Apple emphasized its new "digital lifestyle" applications such as the iLife suite, integrated home entertainment through the Front Row media center and the Safari web browser.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] With the increasing popularity of the internet, Apple offered additional online services, including the .Mac, MobileMe, and later, iCloud products.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] It later began selling third-party applications through the Mac App Store.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Newer versions of Mac OS X also included modifications to the general interface, moving away from the striped gloss and transparency of the initial versions.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Some applications began to use a brushed metal appearance, or non-pinstriped title bar appearance in Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In Mac OS X Leopard (10.5), Apple announced a unification of the interface, with a standardized gray-gradient window style.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2006, the first Intel Macs were released with a specialized version of Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] A key development for the system was the announcement and release of the iPhone from 2007 onwards.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] While Apple's previous iPod media players used a minimal operating system, the iPhone used an operating system based on Mac OS X, which would later be called iPhone OS and then iOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The simultaneous release of two operating systems based on the same frameworks placed tension on Apple, which cited the iPhone as forcing it to delay Mac OS X Leopard.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] However, after Apple opened the iPhone to third-party developers, its commercial success drew attention to Mac OS X, with many iPhone software developers showing interest in Mac development.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2007, Mac OS X Leopard released with universal binary components, allowing installation on both Intel Macs and select PowerPC Macs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] It is also the final release with PowerPC Mac support.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2009, Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6) was the first version of Mac OS X to be built exclusively for Intel Macs and the final release with 32-bit Intel Mac support.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The name was intended to signal its status as an iteration of Leopard, focusing on technical and performance improvements rather than user-facing features; indeed it was explicitly branded to developers as being a 'no new features' release.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Since its release, several OS X or macOS releases (namely OS X Mountain Lion, OS X El Capitan, macOS High Sierra, and macOS Monterey) follow this pattern, with a name derived from its predecessor, similar to the 'tick–tock model' used by Intel.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Starting in 2011 with Mac OS X Lion (10.7) and OS X Mountain Lion (10.8), Apple moved some applications to a highly skeuomorphic style of design inspired by contemporary versions of iOS while simplifying some elements by making controls such as scroll bars fade out when not in use.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In addition, with Lion, Apple ceased to release separate server versions of Mac OS X, selling server tools as a separate downloadable application through the Mac App Store.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2012, with the release of OS X Mountain Lion, the name of the system was officially shortened from Mac OS X to OS X, after the previous version shortened the system name in a similar fashion a year prior.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] That year, Apple removed the head of OS X development, Scott Forstall, and design was changed towards a more minimal direction.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple's new user interface design, using deep color saturation, text-only buttons and a minimal, 'flat' interface, was debuted with iOS 7 in 2013.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] With OS X engineers reportedly working on iOS 7, the version released in 2013, OS X Mavericks (10.9), was something of a transitional release, with some of the skeuomorphic design removed, while most of the general interface of Mavericks remained unchanged.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The next version, OS X Yosemite (10.10), adopted a design similar to iOS 7 but with greater complexity suitable for an interface controlled with a mouse.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] From 2012 onwards, the system has shifted to an annual release schedule similar to that of Mac OS X releases prior to 10.4 Tiger.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] It also steadily cut the cost of updates from Snow Leopard onwards, before removing upgrade fees altogether in OS X Mavericks.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Some journalists and third-party software developers have suggested that this decision, while allowing more rapid feature release, meant less opportunity to focus on stability, with no version of OS X recommendable for users requiring stability and performance above new features.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple's 2015 update, OS X El Capitan (10.11), was announced to focus specifically on stability and performance improvements.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Its successor, macOS Mojave (10.14), was released in 2018, adding a dark mode option and a dynamic wallpaper setting.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] It was succeeded by macOS Catalina (10.15) in 2019, which replaces iTunes with separate apps for different types of media, and introduces the Catalyst system for porting iOS apps.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2020, Apple announced macOS Big Sur (version 11) at that year's WWDC.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This was the first increment in the primary version number of macOS since the release of Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000; updates to macOS Big Sur were given 11.x numbers, matching the version numbering scheme used by Apple's other operating systems.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Big Sur brought major changes to the user interface and was the first version to run on Apple Silicon, based on the ARM architecture.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The numbering system started with Big Sur continued in 2021 with macOS Monterey (12), 2022 with macOS Ventura (13), 2023 with macOS Sonoma (14), and 2024 with macOS Sequoia (15).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] During its Platforms State of the Union event on June 9, 2025, Apple announced that Tahoe would be the final version of macOS to operate on Intel-based Macs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2026, Apple announced macOS Golden Gate (version 27) at WWDC 2026.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] It will be the first version of macOS to run exclusively on Macs with Apple silicon and the last version with full Rosetta 2 functionality.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The Power Mac G5 had special Jaguar builds.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Tiger did not support 64-bit GUI applications, only 64-bit CLI applications.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] 32-bit (but not 64-bit) PowerPC applications were supported on Intel processors with Rosetta.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] 64-bit Intel applications are supported on Apple silicon Macs with Rosetta 2.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] However, Intel-based Macs are unable to run ARM-based applications, such as iOS and iPadOS apps.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] At macOS's core is a POSIX-compliant operating system built on top of the XNU kernel, (which incorporated large parts of FreeBSD kernel) and FreeBSD userland for the standard Unix facilities available from the command line interface.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple has released this family of software as a free and open source operating system named Darwin.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] On top of Darwin, Apple layered a number of components, including the Aqua interface and the Finder, to complete the GUI-based operating system which is macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] With its original introduction as Mac OS X, the system brought a number of new capabilities to provide a more stable and reliable platform than its predecessor, the classic Mac OS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] For example, pre-emptive multitasking and memory protection improved the system's ability to run multiple applications simultaneously without them interrupting or corrupting each other.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Many aspects of macOS's architecture are derived from OPENSTEP, which was designed to be portable, to ease the transition from one platform to another.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] For example, NeXTSTEP was ported from the original 68k-based NeXT workstations to x86 and other architectures before NeXT was purchased by Apple, and OPENSTEP was later ported to the PowerPC architecture as part of the Rhapsody project.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Prior to macOS High Sierra, and on drives other than solid state drives (SSDs), the default file system is HFS+, which it inherited from the classic Mac OS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Operating system designer Linus Torvalds had criticized HFS+, saying it is "probably the worst file system ever", whose design is "actively corrupting user data".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] He criticized the case insensitivity of file names, a design made worse when Apple extended the file system to support Unicode.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The Darwin subsystem in macOS manages the file system, which includes the Unix permissions layer.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Later, another Macworld editor, Dan Frakes, called the procedure of repairing permissions vastly overused.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] He argues that macOS typically handles permissions properly without user interference, and resetting permissions should only be tried when problems emerge.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The architecture of macOS incorporates a layered design: the layered frameworks aid rapid development of applications by providing existing code for common tasks.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple provides its own software development tools, most prominently an integrated development environment called Xcode.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Xcode provides interfaces to compilers that support several programming languages including C, C++, Objective-C, and Swift.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] For the Mac transition to Intel processors, it was modified so that developers could build their applications as a universal binary, which provides compatibility with both the Intel-based and PowerPC-based Macintosh lines.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] First and third-party applications can be controlled programmatically using the AppleScript framework, retained from the classic Mac OS, or using the newer Automator application that offers pre-written tasks that do not require programming knowledge.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple offered two main APIs to develop software natively for macOS: Cocoa and Carbon.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Cocoa was a descendant of APIs inherited from OPENSTEP with no ancestry from the classic Mac OS, while Carbon was an adaptation of classic Mac OS APIs, allowing Mac software to be minimally rewritten to run natively on Mac OS X.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The Cocoa API was created as the result of a 1993 collaboration between NeXT Computer and Sun Microsystems.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This heritage is highly visible for Cocoa developers, since the "NS" prefix is ubiquitous in the framework, standing variously for **N**eXT**S**TEP or **N**eXT/**S**un.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The official OPENSTEP API, published in September 1994, was the first to split the API between Foundation and ApplicationKit and the first to use the "NS" prefix.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Traditionally, Cocoa programs have been mostly written in Objective-C, with Java as an alternative.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Since 2014, Apple has promoted its new programming language Swift as the preferred language for software development on Apple platforms.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple's original plan with macOS was to require all developers to rewrite their software into the Cocoa APIs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This caused much outcry among existing Mac developers, who threatened to abandon the platform rather than invest in a costly rewrite, and the idea was shelved.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] To permit a smooth transition from Mac OS 9 to Mac OS X, the Carbon Application Programming Interface (API) was created.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Applications written with Carbon were initially able to run natively on both classic Mac OS and Mac OS X, although this ability was later dropped as Mac OS X developed.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Carbon was not included in the first product sold as Mac OS X: the little-used original release of Mac OS X Server 1.0, which also did not include the Aqua interface.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple limited further development of Carbon from the release of Leopard onwards and announced that Carbon applications would not run at 64-bit.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] A number of macOS applications continued to use Carbon for some time afterwards, especially ones with heritage dating back to the classic Mac OS and for which updates would be difficult, uneconomic or not necessary.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This included Microsoft Office up to Office 2016, and Photoshop up to CS5.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Early versions of macOS could also run some classic Mac OS applications through the Classic Environment with performance limitations; this feature was removed from 10.5 onwards and all Macs using Intel processors.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Because macOS is POSIX compliant, many software packages written for the other Unix-like systems including Linux can be recompiled to run on it, including many scientific and technical programs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Third-party projects such as Homebrew, Fink, MacPorts and pkgsrc provide pre-compiled or pre-formatted packages.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple and others have provided versions of the X Window System graphical interface which can allow these applications to run with an approximation of the macOS look-and-feel.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The current Apple-endorsed method is the open-source XQuartz project; earlier versions could use the X11 application provided by Apple, or before that the XDarwin project.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apps installed through the Mac App Store run within a sandbox, restricting their ability to exchange information with other applications or modify the core operating system and its features.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This has been cited as an advantage, by allowing users to install apps with confidence that they should not be able to damage their system, but also as a disadvantage due to blocking the Mac App Store's use for professional applications that require elevated privileges.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Applications without any code signature cannot be run by default except from a computer's administrator account.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Some are included with macOS and some sold separately.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This includes iWork, Final Cut Pro, Logic Pro, iLife, and the database application FileMaker.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Numerous other developers also offer software for macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2018, Apple introduced an application layer, codenamed Marzipan, to port iOS apps to macOS. macOS Mojave included ports of four first-party iOS apps including Home and News, and it was announced that the API would be available for third-party developers to use from 2019.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] With macOS Catalina in 2019, the application layer was made available to third-party developers as Mac Catalyst.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Tools such as XPostFacto and patches applied to the installation media have been developed by third parties to enable installation of newer versions of macOS on systems not officially supported by Apple.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Except for features requiring specific hardware such as graphics acceleration or DVD writing, the operating system offers the same functionality on all supported hardware.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] As most Mac hardware components, or components similar to those, since the Intel transition are available for purchase, some technology-capable groups have developed software to install macOS on non-Apple computers.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] These are referred to as Hackintoshes, a portmanteau of the words "hack" and "Macintosh".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This violates Apple's EULA (and is therefore unsupported by Apple technical support, warranties etc.), but communities that cater to personal users, who do not install for resale and profit, have generally been ignored by Apple.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] These self-made computers allow more flexibility and customization of hardware, but at a cost of leaving the user more responsible for their own machine, such as on matter of data integrity or security.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Psystar, a business that attempted to profit from selling macOS on non-Apple certified hardware, was sued by Apple in 2008.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In April 2002, eWeek announced a rumor that Apple had a version of Mac OS X code-named Marklar, which ran on Intel x86 processors.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The idea behind Marklar was to keep Mac OS X running on an alternative platform should Apple become dissatisfied with the progress of the PowerPC platform.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] These rumors subsided until late in May 2005, when various media outlets, such as *The Wall Street Journal* and CNET, announced that Apple would unveil Marklar in the coming months.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] On June 6, 2005, Steve Jobs announced in his keynote address at WWDC that Apple would be making the transition from PowerPC to Intel processors over the following two years, and that Mac OS X would support both platforms during the transition.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Jobs also confirmed rumors that Apple had versions of Mac OS X running on Intel processors for most of its developmental life.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Intel-based Macs would run a new recompiled version of OS X along with Rosetta, a binary translation layer which enables software compiled for PowerPC Mac OS X to run on Intel Mac OS X machines.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The system was included with Mac OS X versions up to version 10.6.8.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple dropped support for Classic mode on the new Intel Macs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Third party emulation software such as Mini vMac, Basilisk II and SheepShaver provided support for some early versions of Mac OS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] A new version of Xcode and the underlying command-line compilers supported building universal binaries that would run on either architecture.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] PowerPC-only software is supported with Apple's official binary translation software, Rosetta, though applications eventually had to be rewritten to run properly on the newer versions released for Intel processors.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple initially encouraged developers to produce universal binaries with support for both PowerPC and Intel.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] PowerPC binaries suffer a performance penalty when run on Intel Macs through Rosetta.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Moreover, some PowerPC software, such as kernel extensions and System Preferences plugins, are not supported on Intel Macs at all.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Plugins for Safari need to be compiled for the same platform as Safari, so when Safari is running on Intel, it requires plug-ins that have been compiled as Intel-only or universal binaries, so PowerPC-only plug-ins will not work.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] While Intel Macs can run PowerPC, Intel, and universal binaries, PowerPC Macs support only universal and PowerPC builds.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Support for the PowerPC platform was dropped following the transition.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2009, Apple announced at WWDC that Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard would drop support for PowerPC processors and be Intel-only.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Rosetta continued to be offered as an optional download or installation choice in Snow Leopard before it was discontinued with Mac OS X 10.7 Lion.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In addition, new versions of Mac OS X first- and third-party software increasingly required Intel processors, including new versions of iLife, iWork, Aperture and Logic Pro.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Rumors of Apple shifting Macs from Intel to in-house ARM processors used by iOS devices began circulating as early as 2011, and ebbed and flowed throughout the 2010s.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Rumors intensified in 2020, when numerous reports announced that the company would announce its shift to its custom processors at WWDC.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple officially announced its shift to processors designed in-house on June 22, 2020, at WWDC 2020, with the transition planned to last for approximately two years.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The first release of macOS to support ARM was macOS Big Sur.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Big Sur and later versions support Universal 2 binaries, which are applications consisting of both Intel (x86-64) and Apple silicon (AArch64) binaries; when launched, only the appropriate binary is run.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Additionally, Intel binaries can be run on Apple silicon-based Macs using the Rosetta 2 binary translation software.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The transition was completed at WWDC 2023 with the announcement of the Apple silicon Mac Pro, ending the transition in 3 years, slightly behind schedule.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The change in processor architecture allows Macs with ARM processors to be able to run iOS and iPadOS apps natively.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The macOS user interface places a menu bar along the top edge of the screen, containing the Apple menu and application menus at the start, and status menus at the end.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The Dock is placed along the bottom of the screen by default, and contains icons for pinned and active applications, file and folder shortcuts, minimized windows, and the Trash (or Bin).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] On most windows, the start of the title bar has three buttons resembling a horizontal traffic light, which respectively close, minimize, and resize the window.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple has continued to change aspects of the macOS appearance and design, particularly with tweaks to the appearance of windows and the menu bar.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Since 2012, Apple has sold almost all of its Mac models with high-resolution Retina displays, and macOS and its APIs have extensive support for resolution-independent development on supporting high-resolution displays.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Reviewers have described Apple's support for the technology as superior to that on Windows.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The human interface guidelines published by Apple for macOS are followed by many applications, giving them consistent user interface and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Services available in every Cocoa application include spelling and grammar checkers, special characters palette, color picker, font chooser and dictionary.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The graphics system OpenGL composites windows onto the screen to allow hardware-accelerated drawing.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] This technology, introduced in version 10.2, is called Quartz Extreme, a component of Quartz.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Quartz's internal imaging model correlates well with the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, making it easy to output PDF to multiple devices.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] As a side result, PDF viewing and creating PDF documents from any application are built-in features.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Reflecting its popularity with design users, macOS also has system support for a variety of professional video and image formats and includes an extensive pre-installed font library, featuring many prominent brand-name designs.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] A major addition between the classic Mac OS and the first major release of Mac OS X was Aqua, a design language with water-like elements.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Every window element, text, graphic, or widget was drawn on-screen using spatial anti-aliasing technology.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The preexisting ColorSync technology was improved and built into the core drawing engine, to provide color matching for printing and multimedia professionals.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Drop shadows were added around windows and isolated text elements to provide a sense of depth.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] New interface elements were integrated, including sheets (dialog boxes attached to specific windows) and drawers, which would slide out and provide options.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The use of soft edges, translucent colors, and pinstripes, similar to the hardware design of the first iMacs, brought more texture and color to the user interface when compared to what Mac OS 9 and Mac OS X Server 1.0's Platinum appearance had offered.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Third-party developers started producing skins for customizable applications and other operating systems which mimicked the Aqua appearance.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] To some extent, Apple has used the successful transition to this design as leverage, at various times threatening legal action against people who make or distribute software with an interface the company says is derived from its copyrighted design.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Following a similar design change in iOS 7, OS X Yosemite shifted to a flat design language, simplifying many of the Aqua elements and icons.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In 2025, macOS Tahoe adopted the Liquid Glass design language, which was inspired in part by Aqua.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The Finder is a file browser allowing quick access to all areas of the computer, which has been modified throughout subsequent releases of macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Quick Look has been part of the Finder since version 10.5.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] It allows for dynamic previews of files, including videos and multi-page documents without opening any other applications.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Spotlight, a file searching technology which has been integrated into the Finder since version 10.4, allows rapid real-time searches of data files; mail messages; photos; and other information based on item properties (metadata) or content.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple added Exposé in version 10.3 (called Mission Control since version 10.7), a feature which includes three functions to help accessibility between windows and desktop.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Its functions are to instantly reveal all open windows as thumbnails for easy navigation to different tasks, display all open windows as thumbnails from the current application, and hide all windows to access the desktop.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] FileVault is optional encryption of the user's files with the 128-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES-128).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Sync Services allows applications to access a centralized extensible database for various elements of user data, including calendar and contact items.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] The operating system then managed conflicting edits and data consistency.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple has developed support for emoji characters by including the proprietary Apple Color Emoji font.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple has also connected macOS with social networks such as Twitter and Facebook through the addition of share buttons for content such as pictures and text.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Apple has brought several applications and features that originally debuted in iOS, its mobile operating system, to macOS, notably the intelligent personal assistant Siri, which was introduced in version 10.12 of macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] There are 47 system languages available in macOS for the user at the moment of installation; the system language is used throughout the entire operating system environment.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Input methods for typing in dozens of scripts can be chosen independently of the system language.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Updates have added increased support for Chinese characters and interconnections with popular social networks in China.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] macOS can be updated using the Software Update settings pane in System Settings or the `softwareupdate` command line utility.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Until OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion, a separate Software Update application performed this functionality.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In Mountain Lion and later, this was merged into the Mac App Store application, although the underlying update mechanism remains unchanged and is fundamentally different from the download mechanism used when purchasing an App Store application.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] In macOS 10.14 Mojave, the updating function was moved again to the Software Update settings pane.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] Most Macs receive six or seven years of macOS updates.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p01] After a new major release of macOS, the previous two releases still receive occasional updates, but many security vulnerabilities are only patched in the latest macOS release.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X versions were named after big cats, with the exception of Mac OS X Server 1.0 and the original public beta, from Mac OS X 10.0 until OS X 10.9 Mavericks, when Apple switched to using California locations.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Prior to its release, version 10.0 was code named internally at Apple as "Cheetah", and Mac OS X 10.1 was code named internally as "Puma".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] After the immense buzz surrounding Mac OS X 10.2, codenamed "Jaguar", Apple's product marketing began openly using the code names to promote the operating system.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.3 was marketed as "Panther", Mac OS X 10.4 as "Tiger", Mac OS X 10.5 as "Leopard", Mac OS X 10.6 as "Snow Leopard", Mac OS X 10.7 as "Lion", OS X 10.8 as "Mountain Lion", and OS X 10.9 as "Mavericks".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] "Panther", "Tiger" and "Leopard" are registered as trademarks of Apple, but "Cheetah", "Puma" and "Jaguar" have never been registered.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple has also registered "Lynx" and "Cougar" as trademarks, though these were allowed to lapse.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Computer retailer Tiger Direct sued Apple for its use of the name "Tiger".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] On May 16, 2005, a US federal court in the Southern District of Florida ruled that Apple's use did not infringe on Tiger Direct's trademark.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] On September 13, 2000, Apple released a US$29.95 "preview" version of Mac OS X, internally codenamed Kodiak, to gain feedback from users.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The "PB", as it was known, marked the first public availability of the Aqua interface and Apple made many changes to the UI based on customer feedback.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X Public Beta expired and ceased to function in Spring 2001.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] On March 24, 2001, Apple released Mac OS X 10.0 (internally codenamed Cheetah).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The initial version was slow, incomplete, and had very few applications available at launch, mostly from independent developers.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] While many critics suggested that the operating system was not ready for mainstream adoption, they recognized the importance of its initial launch as a base on which to improve.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Simply releasing Mac OS X was received by the Macintosh community as a great accomplishment, for attempts to overhaul the Mac OS had been underway since 1996, and had been delayed by countless setbacks.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Later that year, on September 25, 2001, Mac OS X 10.1 (internally codenamed Puma) was released.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It featured increased performance and provided missing features, such as DVD playback.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple released 10.1 as a free upgrade CD for 10.0 users, in addition to the $129 boxed version for people running Mac OS 9.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It was discovered that the upgrade CDs were full install CDs that could be used with Mac OS 9 systems by removing a specific file; Apple later re-released the CDs in an actual stripped-down format that did not facilitate installation on such systems.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] On January 7, 2002, Apple announced that Mac OS X was to be the default operating system for all Macintosh products by the end of that month.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] On August 23, 2002, Apple followed up with Mac OS X 10.2 Jaguar, the first release to use its code name as part of the branding.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It brought significant performance improvements, and an updated version of Aqua's visual design.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The Happy Mac icon — which had appeared during the Mac OS startup sequence since the original Macintosh — was replaced with a gray Apple logo.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X v10.3 Panther was released on October 24, 2003.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It significantly improved performance and incorporated the most extensive update yet to the user interface.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Support for some early G3 computers such as "beige" Power Macs and "WallStreet" PowerBooks was discontinued.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.4 Tiger was released on April 29, 2005.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple stated that Tiger contained more than 200 new features.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] As with Panther, certain older machines were no longer supported; Tiger requires a Mac with 256 MB of RAM and a built-in FireWire port.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Among the new features, Tiger introduced Spotlight, Dashboard, Smart Folders, updated Mail program with Smart Mailboxes, QuickTime 7, Safari 2, Automator, VoiceOver, Core Image and Core Video.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The initial release of the Apple TV used a modified version of Tiger with a different graphical interface and fewer applications and services.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] On January 10, 2006, Apple released the first Intel-based Macs along with the 10.4.4 update to Tiger.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] This operating system functioned identically on the PowerPC-based Macs and the new Intel-based machines, with the exception of the Intel release lacking support for the Classic environment.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard was released on October 26, 2007.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It was called by Apple "the largest update of Mac OS X".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Leopard supports both PowerPC- and Intel x86-based Macintosh computers; support for the G3 processor was dropped and the G4 processor required a minimum clock rate of 867 MHz, and at least 512 MB of RAM to be installed.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The single DVD works for all supported Macs (including 64-bit machines).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] New features include a new look, an updated Finder, Time Machine, Spaces, Boot Camp pre-installed, full support for 64-bit applications (including graphical applications), new features in Mail and iChat, and a number of new security features.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Leopard is an Open Brand UNIX 03 registered product on the Intel platform.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It was also the first BSD-based OS to receive UNIX 03 certification.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Leopard dropped support for the Classic Environment and all Classic applications.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It was the final version of Mac OS X to support the PowerPC architecture.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard was released on August 28, 2009.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Rather than delivering big changes to the appearance and end user functionality like the previous releases of Mac OS X, Snow Leopard focused on "under the hood" changes, increasing the performance, efficiency, and stability of the operating system.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Snow Leopard only supported machines with Intel CPUs, required at least 1 GB of RAM, and dropped default support for applications built for the PowerPC architecture (Rosetta could be installed as an additional component to retain support for PowerPC-only applications).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Snow Leopard also featured new 64-bit technology capable of supporting greater amounts of RAM, improved support for multi-core processors through Grand Central Dispatch, and advanced GPU performance with OpenCL.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The 10.6.6 update also introduced support for the Mac App Store, Apple's digital distribution platform for macOS applications.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.7 Lion was released on July 20, 2011.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It brought developments made in Apple's iOS, such as an easily navigable display of installed applications called Launchpad and a greater use of multi-touch gestures, to the Mac.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] This release removed Rosetta, making it incompatible with PowerPC applications.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Changes made to the GUI include auto-hiding scrollbars that only appear when they are used, and Mission Control which unifies Exposé, Spaces, Dashboard, and full-screen applications within a single interface.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple also made changes to applications: they resume in the same state as they were before they were closed, similar to iOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion was released on July 25, 2012.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Following the release of Lion the previous year, it was the first of the annual rather than two-yearly updates to OS X (and later macOS), which also closely aligned with the annual iOS operating system updates.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It incorporates some features seen in iOS 5, which include Game Center, support for iMessage in the new Messages messaging application, and Reminders as a to-do list app separate from iCal (which is renamed as Calendar, like the iOS app).
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It also includes support for storing iWork documents in iCloud.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Notification Center, which makes its debut in Mountain Lion, is a desktop version similar to the one in iOS 5.0 and higher.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Application pop-ups are now concentrated on the corner of the screen, and the Center itself is pulled from the right side of the screen.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mountain Lion also includes more Chinese features including support for Baidu as an option for Safari search engine, QQ, 163.com and 126.com services for Mail, Contacts and Calendar, Youku, Tudou and Sina Weibo are integrated into share sheets.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Starting with Mountain Lion, Apple software updates (including the OS) are distributed via the App Store.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] This updating mechanism replaced the Apple Software Update utility.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.9 Mavericks was released on October 22, 2013.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It is a free upgrade to all users running Snow Leopard or later with a 64-bit Intel processor.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Its changes include the addition of the previously iOS-only Maps and iBooks applications, improvements to the Notification Center, enhancements to several applications, and many under-the-hood improvements.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.10 Yosemite was released on October 16, 2014.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It features a redesigned user interface similar to that of iOS 7, intended to feature a more minimal, text-based 'flat' design, with use of translucency effects and intensely saturated colors.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple's showcase new feature in Yosemite is Handoff, which enables users with iPhones running iOS 8.1 or later to answer phone calls, receive and send SMS messages, and complete unfinished iPhone emails on their Mac.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] As of OS X 10.10.3, Photos replaced iPhoto and Aperture.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.11 El Capitan was released on September 30, 2015.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Similar to Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard, Apple described this release as emphasizing "refinements to the Mac experience" and "improvements to system performance".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Refinements include public transport built into the Maps application, GUI improvements to the Notes application, adopting San Francisco as the system font for clearer legibility, and the introduction of System Integrity Protection.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The Metal API, first introduced in iOS 8, was also included in this operating system for "all Macs since 2012".
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] According to Apple, Metal accelerates system-level rendering by up to 50 percent, resulting in faster graphics performance for everyday apps.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Metal also delivers up to 10 times faster draw call performance for more fluid experience in games and pro apps.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.12 Sierra was released to the public on September 20, 2016.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] New features include the addition of Siri, optimized storage, and updates to Photos, Messages, and iTunes.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.13 High Sierra was released to the public on September 25, 2017.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Like OS X El Capitan and OS X Mountain Lion, High Sierra is a refinement-based update having very few new features visible to the user, including updates to Safari, Photos, and Mail, among other changes.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The major change under the hood is the switch to the Apple File System, optimized for the solid-state storage used in most new Mac computers.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.14 Mojave was released on September 24, 2018.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The update introduced a system-wide dark mode and several new apps lifted from iOS, such as Apple News.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It was the first version to require a GPU that supports Metal.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mojave also changed the system software update mechanism from the App Store (where it had been since OS X Mountain Lion) to a new panel in System Preferences.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.15 Catalina was released on October 7, 2019.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Updates included enhanced voice control, and bundled apps for music, video, and podcasts that together replace the functions of iTunes, and the ability to use an iPad as an external monitor.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Catalina officially dropped support for 32-bit applications.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Big Sur was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 22, 2020, and it was made available to the general public on November 12, 2020.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] This is the first time the major version number of the operating system has been incremented since the Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It brings Arm support, new icons, and aesthetic user interface changes to the system.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Ventura was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 6, 2022 and released on October 24, 2022.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It came with the redesigned System Preferences (named System Settings) to a more iOS-like design, and the new Freeform, Weather and Clock apps that run natively on Mac.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Users can use an iPhone as a webcam for video conferencing with Continuity Camera.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Siri's appearance was changed to look more like the versions on iOS 14 and iPadOS 14.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Mail introduced schedule send and undo send for emails, and Message also got the ability to undo send and edit messages.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Stage Manager was introduced as a new way to organize all open windows in a desktop.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Maps gained the feature for multiple-stop routes, Metal 3 was added with support for spatial and temporal image upscaling, Lockdown Mode was added to reduce the risk of a cyberattack, and the ability to play ambient background sounds was added as an accessibility feature in System Settings.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Sonoma was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 5, 2023, and released on September 26, 2023. macOS Sonoma revamped widgets—they can now be placed anywhere on the desktop.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Game mode optimizes game performance by prioritizing gaming tasks and allocating more GPU and CPU capacity to the game, and by doing so is able to provide smoother frame rates for gameplay.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The Spotlight Search bar and all app icons were made even more rounded, smoother animations were implemented for notifications and the lock screen, and new slow-motion screensavers of different locations worldwide were added.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] When logged in, they gradually slow down and become the desktop wallpaper.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Sequoia was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 10, 2024.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Tahoe was announced on June 9, 2025, during the WWDC 2025 keynote address.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It is the first macOS version to feature the new Liquid Glass design introduced across Apple operating systems that year.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It is also the first macOS to use Apple's new release number convention, which gives all of Apple's operating systems the same version number.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Golden Gate was announced at WWDC on June 8, 2026.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] It introduces visual intelligence, redesigns Siri, and brings Apple Intelligence features to apps such as Safari and Passwords.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Golden Gate also improves Liquid Glass on windows and sidebars, and allows users to adjust the system opacity.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple publishes Apple Platform Security documents to lay out the security protections built into macOS and Mac hardware.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] These prevent some vulnerabilities within macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Only the latest major release of macOS (macOS Tahoe as of June 2026) receives patches for all known security vulnerabilities.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] The previous two releases receive some security updates, but not for all vulnerabilities known to Apple.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] macOS Ventura added support for Rapid Security Response (RSR) updates and Lockdown Mode.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Rapid Security Response updates may require a reboot, but take less than a minute to install.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] In an analysis, Hackintosh developer Mykola Grymalyuk noted that RSR updates can only fix userland vulnerabilities, and cannot patch the macOS kernel.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Lockdown Mode is an optional security feature designed to provide extreme protection for users who may be at risk of targeted cyberattacks, such as journalists, activists, and public figures.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] This mode significantly alters the functionality of the device to enhance security against sophisticated threats, particularly from spyware and state-sponsored attacks.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple says most people are never impacted by these attacks.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] In its earlier years, Mac OS X enjoyed a near-absence of the types of malware and spyware that have affected Microsoft Windows users. macOS has a smaller usage share compared to Windows.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Worms, as well as potential vulnerabilities, were noted in 2006, which led some industry analysts and anti-virus companies to issue warnings that Apple's Mac OS X is not immune to malware.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Increasing market share coincided with additional reports of a variety of attacks.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] In early 2011, Mac OS X experienced a large increase in malware attacks, and malware such as Mac Defender, MacProtector, and MacGuard was seen as an increasing problem for Mac users.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] At first, the malware installer required the user to enter the administrative password, but later versions installed without user input.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Initially, Apple support staff were instructed not to assist in the removal of the malware or admit the existence of the malware issue, but as the malware spread, a support document was issued.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple announced an OS X update to fix the problem.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] An estimated 100,000 users were affected.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] Apple releases security updates for macOS regularly, as well as signature files containing malware signatures for Xprotect, an anti-malware feature part of File Quarantine present since Mac OS X Snow Leopard.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] As of January 2023, macOS is the second-most widely used general-purpose desktop operating system used on the World Wide Web following Microsoft Windows, with a 15.33% usage share, according to statistics compiled by StatCounter.
[src:appkit-macos/macos-p02] As a device company, Apple has mostly promoted macOS to sell Macs, with promotion of macOS updates focused on existing users, promotion at Apple Store and other retail partners, or through events for developers.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] In Apple's macOS operating system, **Quartz** is the Quartz 2D and Quartz Compositor part of the Core Graphics framework.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] Quartz includes both a 2D renderer in Core Graphics and the composition engine that sends instructions to the graphics card.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] Because of this vertical nature, *Quartz* is often synonymous with *Core Graphics*.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] In a general sense, *Quartz* or *Quartz technologies* can refer to almost every part of the macOS graphics model from the rendering layer down to the compositor including Core Image and Core Video.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] Quartz 2D is the primary two-dimensional (2D) text and graphics rendering library: It directly supports Aqua by displaying two-dimensional graphics to create the user interface, including on-the-fly rendering and anti-aliasing.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] Quartz can render text with sub-pixel precision; graphics are limited to more traditional anti-aliasing, which is the default mode of operation but can be turned off.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] In Mac OS X 10.4 Tiger, Apple introduced Quartz 2D Extreme, enabling Quartz 2D to offload rendering to compatible GPUs.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] However, GPU rendering was not enabled by default due to potential video redraw issues or kernel panics.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] In Mac OS X v10.5 Quartz 2D Extreme was renamed to QuartzGL.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] The Quartz Compositor is the compositing engine used by macOS.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] In Mac OS X Jaguar and later, the Quartz Compositor can use the graphics accelerator (GPU) to vastly improve composition performance.
[src:appkit-macos/quartz-graphics-layer] This technology is known as Quartz Extreme and is enabled automatically on systems with supported graphics cards.
